Name: Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa
Comments:
Male feminist, wrote *Declamatio de nobilitate et praecellentia foeminei 
sexus* (*Declamation on the Nobility and Preeminence of the Female Sex)*, a 
book pronouncing the theological and moral superiority of women

Name: Abigail Adams
Comments: Wife of John Adams and mother of John Quincy Adams

Name: Eleanor Butler
Comments: One of the Ladies of Llangollen

Name: Olympe de Gouges
Comments:
Playwright and political activist who wrote the Declaration of the Rights 
of Woman and of the Female Citizen in 1791

Name: Charles Fourier
Comments:
Socialist feminist; philosopher; credited with coining the (French) word 
"féministe"

Name: John Neal
Comments: Writer, critic, and first American women's rights lecturer

Name: Sarah Ponsonby
Comments: One of the Ladies of Llangollen

Name: Sojourner Truth
Comments:
First-wave feminist; abolitionist, women's rights activist, speaker, 
women's rights speech "Ain't I a Woman?"

Name: Mary Wollstonecraft
Comments:
Early pioneer proto-feminist. Author of *A Vindication of the Rights of 
Woman*

Name: Jane Addams
Comments:
Feminist; Women's Suffrage advocate; Major social activist, president Women's 
International League for Peace and Freedom

Name: Elizabeth Garrett Anderson
Comments:
Feminist, suffragist; first Englishwoman to qualify as a physician and 
surgeon in the UK; co-founder of first hospital staffed by women

Name: Amelia Bloomer
Comments:
Suffragist, publisher and editor of *The Lily*, advocated for many women's 
issues

Name: Carrie Chapman Catt
Comments:
Suffrage leader, president of the National American Woman Suffrage 
Association, founder of League of Women Voters and the International 
Alliance of Women

Name: Margaret Fuller
Comments:
Transcendentalist, critic, advocate for women's education, author of *Woman 
in the Nineteenth Century*

Name: Emma Goldman
Comments:
Individualist feminist; Russian-American campaigner for birth control and 
other rights

Name: Grace Greenwood
Comments:
First woman reporter on the *New York Times* payroll, advocate for social 
reform and women's rights

Name: Nellie McClung
Comments: Feminist and suffragist; part of The Famous Five

Name: Emmeline Pankhurst
Comments:
Suffragette; one of the founders and the leader of the British suffragette 
movement

Name: Kate Sheppard
Comments:
Influential in winning voting rights for women in 1893 (the first country 
and national election in which women were allowed to vote)

Name: Elizabeth Cady Stanton
Comments:
Social activist, abolitionist, suffragist, organizer of the 1848  Women's 
Rights Convention, co-founder of the National Woman Suffrage Association 
and the International Council of Women

Name: Lucy Stone
Comments:
Orator, organizer of the first National Women's Rights Convention, founder 
of the *Woman's Journal*, and first recorded American woman to retain her 
surname after marriage

Name: Táhirih
Comments: Bábí poet, theologian, and proponent of women's rights in 19th-century Iran

Name: Victoria Woodhull
Comments:
First-wave feminist; suffragist, organizer, innovator, first woman to run 
for U.S. presidency

Name: Madeleine Albright
Comments:
64thUnited States Secretary of State, and at the time, the highest ranking 
woman in US history. She is a staunch supporter of the feminist cause.

Name: Lucy Burns
Comments: Suffragette; suffragist and women's rights activist

Name: Eva Cox
Comments: Sociologist; long-time member of the Women's Electoral Lobby

Name: Elisabeth Freeman
Comments: Suffragist and civil rights activist, participated in the Suffrage Hikes

Name: Germaine Greer
Comments: Second-wave feminist, author of *The Female Eunuch*

Name: Claudia Jones
Country: United Kingdom, United States, Trinidad and Tobago

Name: Inez Milholland
Comments:
Key participant in the National Woman's Party and the Woman Suffrage Parade 
of 1913

Name: Diane Nash
Comments: 1960s Civil Rights Movement leader and organizer, voting rights proponent

Name: Christabel Pankhurst
Comments: Suffragette; co-founder and leader of the Women's Social and Political Union

Name: Alice Paul
Comments:
One of the leaders of the 1910s Women's Voting Rights Movement for the 19th 
Amendment; founder of National Woman's Party, initiator of the Silent 
Sentinels and the 1913 Women's Suffrage Parade, author of the proposed Equal 
Rights Amendment

Name: Margaret Sanger
Comments:
Socialist feminist; Founder of American Birth Control League; co-founder 
and long-time president of Planned Parenthood; writer, nurse

Name: Gloria Steinem
Comments:
Second-wave feminist; Socialist feminist; radical feminist; anti-pornography 
feminist; writer

Name: Doris Stevens
Comments:
Organizer for National American Women Suffrage Association and the National 
Woman's Party, prominent Silent Sentinels participant, author *Jailed for 
Freedom*

Name: Sandy Stone
Comments:
Transfeminist; Second-wave feminist; Theorist, author, and performance 
artist

Name: Dorothy Thompson
Comments:
Buffalo and New York suffragist, later an influential journalist and radio 
broadcaster

Name: Sara Ahmed
Comments:
British-Australian academic working at the intersection of feminist theory, 
queer theory, critical race theory and postcolonialism

Name: Alison Bechdel
Comments: Cartoonist, author; creator of the Bechdel test

Name: Jeanne Córdova
Comments: Second-wave feminist; lesbian and gay rights activist

Name: Geena Davis
Comments: Actor, founder of Geena Davis Institute on Gender in Media

Name: Andrea Dworkin
Comments: Radical feminist; anti-prostitution feminist; anti-pornography feminist

Name: Shirin Ebadi
Comments:
Muslim feminist; activist, Nobel Peace Prize winner for her efforts for the 
rights of women and children

Name: Shulamith Firestone
Comments:
Second-wave feminist; radical feminist; Redstockings; New York Radical 
Feminists; New York Radical Women

Name: Sunitha Krishnan
Comments:
Indian social activist and chief functionary and co-founder of Prajwala, an 
institution that assists trafficked women, girls and transgender people in 
finding shelter, giving education and employment

Name: Robin Morgan
Comments:
Second-wave feminist; radical feminist; anti-pornography feminist; New York 
Radical Women

Name: Camille Paglia
Comments:
Dissident feminist, academic, author of *Sexual Personae: Art and Decadence 
from Nefertiti to Emily Dickinson* (1990)

Name: Alice Schwarzer
Comments:
Second-wave feminist; anti-pornography feminist; journalist and publisher 
of the magazine *Emma*

Name: John Stoltenberg
Comments: Second-wave feminist; radical feminist; anti-pornography feminist

Name: Emma Watson
Comments: Actor, feminist, United Nations Women Goodwill Ambassador

Name: Joss Whedon
Comments:
Previously listed as a male feminist, he generated a toxic work environment 
for many women in his shows

Name: Ellen Willis
Comments:
Second-wave feminist; radical feminist; sex-positive feminist; Redstockings; 
New York Radical Women

Name: Malala Yousafzai
Comments: Pakistani feminist activist for female education

Name: Meghan Murphy
Comments: Journalist; radical feminist; anti-sex industry feminist
